Landing Location: Unknown
Additional Information: The 1984 tests possibly took place over the course of several months rather than on the same day. What we know is that North Korea carried out 6 tests. We also know that the missiles were caried out at the Tonghae launching station. We also know that 3 of the tests succeeded and that 2 or 3 failed. We do not know exactly which ones were failures and which ones were successes. We also do not know exactly when these tests took place except that it was between April and September of 1984. You should read the information about these first tests not as events that certainly took place exactly as entered but as our best estimates as to what occured in a secret program within one of the most secret regimes in the world. Information in later years is much more complete than information in the early years of this program.

Additional Information: It is possible this was a Scud-C. The missiles travelled a relatively short distance however, so short that South Korea initially assumed these were a KN-02 test. They later revised their assessment of these missiles as being Scuds. The range of this test puts these missiles on par with the Scud-B, however, North Korea has not launched any of those in a long time. It is also possible North Korea purposely targetted the missile in such a way as to limit its range. At this point, evidence is not really clear.

Landing Location: Sea of Japan or East Sea
Additional Information: This test actually took place at a ski resort just outside Wonson. The resort, which was under contruction at the time, is called the Masikryong Ski Resort. The coordinates for this test were actually about: 39.065962, 127.250257. This is about 23  (about 14 mi) southwest of the airport we originally believed the test occured. This ski resort itself is an interesting choice to hold this test at. North Korea hopes to host a few events from the 2018 Winter Olympic Games at the resort. It seems somewhat ironic to host a few Olympic events where a missile test was carried out designed to intimidate neighbors.

Additional Information: The missile exploded shortly after launch. It was detected and tracked by United States Strategic Command (STRATCOM). Reportedly, South Korea did not detect the launch. North Korea has also not released photographs of the test making it extremely difficult for 3rd party observers to confirm the location and the type of missile used in the launch. While this is listed as confirmed, the missile is only presumed to be a Musudan. STRATCOM stated it was a Musudan in its press release, however, follwing the Polaris-2 test a few months later, many have speculated it was an early Polaris-2 test. Others have hypothesized the missile was something new altogether.

Satellite images of the airbase show two large scortch martks on the runway seeming to indicate explosions.

Landing Location: Sea of Japan or East Sea
Additional Information: This was the first known test of a land based version of the Polaris-1. The missile is solid fueled which means it is much easier to launch on short notice. This missile was tested only a few kilometers away from the failed October tests prompting speculation those tests were of this missile system.

Launch Agency/Authority: Hwasong Artillery Units of the KPA Strategic Forces
Landing Location: Sea of Japan or East Sea
Additional Information: North Korea launched these 4 missiles almost simultaneously. It is hypothesized that North Korea was practicing overwhelming THAAD and conducting a simulated attack on the US Marine Corps Airbase in Japan, Iwakuni. As a response to this test, the US deployed THAAD to South Korea ahead of schedule. The apogees and distance travelled for each missile are the averages according to reports, exact distances for each missile are unknown. There were early reports of a fifth missile launch accompanying these four, however, no evidence has surfaced of a launch actually taking place. North Korea may have originally planned to launch five but had to scrub the fifth test for unknown reasons.

Additional Information: The given trajectory of 60/190 is very strange. The missile appears to have been in the air a total of 9 minutes. Initially suspected of being a KN-15, reports have since surfaced that it was a smaller Scud variant. It is likely North Korea was attempting something new with this missile or it suffered some sort of failure midway through the flight. Following a test on April 16 at the same location information leaked seems to suggest North Korea is developing some sort of anti-ship ballistic missile dubbed the KN-17.

Landing Location: N/A
Additional Information: The missile appears to have blown up almost instantly. The test came the day after Kim Il Sung's 105th birthday. At the parade celebrating the day, North Korea displayed several new missiles. The test prompted speculation that North Korea had attempted to test one of those. Some news reports reported that US cyber attacks were responsible for the missile's failure. Other sources though were skeptical. Information released in the days afterwards suggests the test was of a new missile system called the KN-17.

Landing Location: N/A
Additional Information: Initial reports were confusing and suggested multiple launches. Eventually it was determined that only a single launch took place. Reports indicate the missile suffered a catastrophic failure shortly after launch and was destroyed. The launch here is recorded to have occurred at the Pukchang Airfield however reports from PACOM state that the test occurred "near" the airfield. Given that the test failed, North Korea is unlikely to release pictures of the event making it difficult to determine the exact location and the type of missile tested.
